I am deeply saddened by the passing of Scott David “Dave” Parks of Chester, NJ. 

For decades, Dave dedicated his life to serving others as a proud lifetime member of the Chester Volunteer Fire Department, beginning in 1967. He will be remembered not only for his service, but also for the kindness and commitment he brought to his community. 

My thoughts and prayers are with his family, friends, and all who had the privilege of knowing him.

This weekend, Team Kean joined the Raritan Borough community for the 2025 Basilone Parade. This annual tradition honors World War II war hero John Basilone, the only enlisted Marine to receive both the Congressional Medal of Honor and the Navy Cross. 
 
It was an honor to recognize this year's Co-Grand Marshals as well. World War II veterans Benjamin Jackson and Gregory "Roy" Ruffa were presented with American flags and certificates of appreciation during the parade.
 
Fittingly, on #NationalCentenariansDay, both men are also centenarians: 
🇺🇸 Benjamin Jackson, 101, resides in Basking Ridge and served as a Marine in WWII.
🇺🇸 Gregory Ruffa, 100, of Raritan served as a WWII fighter pilot.

We are immensely grateful for their service and are proud to celebrate their remarkable lives alongside the legacy of John Basilone.

National Centenarian's Day is today! This special day honors those reaching 100 years and beyond, celebrating their wisdom, experiences, and contributions to our communities.

If you have a friend or loved one celebrating a centennial birthday this year, please call my District Office at (908) 547-3307. I would be honored to recognize them for this extraordinary achievement!

As our 2025 Law Enforcement Hometown Heroes program comes to a close, it is my honor recognize #NJ07 Officer Brandon Hull of the @PhillipsburgPD for our final week.
 
Earlier this year, Officer Hull responded to a shooting outside a local daycare where nearly 20 rounds had been fired. Remaining vigilant under pressure, he identified a suspect attempting to flee the scene and, along with fellow officers, initiated a felony vehicle stop. That decisive action led to the arrest of a dangerous individual and the recovery of a handgun with an illegal extended magazine.
 
Officer Hull's courage and commitment to safeguarding the citizens of Phillipsburg reflect the very best of law enforcement. On behalf of NJ-07, thank you to Officer Hull and the entire Phillipsburg Police Department for your unwavering dedication and service to the community.

Patrick the pit bull lived an extraordinary and impactful life. 
 
Over a decade ago, Patrick endured horrific abuse where he was starved, emaciated, and discarded down a trash chute. After being nursed back to health, this resilient pup went on to live another 15 years and leaves behind a tremendous legacy for animal welfare. 
 
His miraculous story inspired 'Patrick's Law,' legislation I sponsored in the New Jersey State Senate to strengthen penalties for animal cruelty and protect countless other animals from suffering. 
 
Rest in Peace, Miracle Dog 🐾

If you require assistance with a federal agency, have any questions or concerns, or want to learn more about #NJ07, please contact my office.

Today marks 34 years since Armenia gained independence from the Soviet Union. Armenia’s Independence Day reflects decades of struggle for self-determination and the creation of a sovereign nation.

It is a testament to the resilience of the Armenian people and their enduring commitment to freedom. As we celebrate Armenia’s rich cultural heritage, we also remember that its independence remains under threat from ongoing violence and aggression by Azerbaijan.

My thoughts are with Armenia and the people of Artsakh as they continue their fight for sovereignty, democracy, and the right to exist in peace.

This afternoon, I was honored to receive the MITRE Health Defender of the Year Award from the John P. Mayhugh Foundation (@JPM_Foundation), a nonprofit dedicated to preserving John Powell Mayhugh’s legacy.

I had the privilege of meeting with Mary Lowe Mayhugh and Rhys O’Neill to discuss their mission of raising awareness for Post-Traumatic Stress (PTS), Traumatic Brain Injury (TBI), and other brain and behavioral health challenges in the military community, and the full range of therapies and treatments that support our service members.

Today, I had the pleasure of meeting with several New Jersey members of the American Occupational Therapy Association (AOTA).

We discussed their support for legislation affecting occupational therapy practitioners, their clients, and the future of the profession. 

Thank you to @AOTAInc for visiting and helping us continue to strengthen the field.

Two years ago, the world witnessed the forced displacement and ethnic cleansing of over 100,000 Armenians from their ancestral homeland of Artsakh (Nagorno-Karabakh) at the hands of Azerbaijan.

Today, here in New Jersey and across Armenian communities, we remember the families still enduring the loss of their homeland, culture, and identity.

I will continue to stand with these families in their right to return home and live in Artsakh, as their ancestors have for thousands of years.

On National POW/MIA Recognition Day, we honor the servicemembers who endured captivity as prisoners of war and those who remain missing in action.

Today, I ask you to join me in honoring their courage and sacrifice in defense of our great nation, and in recognizing the families who continue to wait, hope, and keep their loved ones’ memories alive.

They are not forgotten.

We discussed key issues facing materials suppliers nationwide, including strengthening supply chain resiliency, advancing workforce development, and how to make the permitting process more efficient.

Aubrey has been a tireless advocate for childhood cancer, and I have had the privilege of meeting with her many times in DC and in the district to discuss childhood cancer issues and how I can continue supporting these efforts in Congress.

We discussed the company’s move to our district, the FDA’s August approval of Tonmya, the first new treatment for fibromyalgia in more than 15 years, and their work developing non-opioid pain treatments for migraines.

AM radio remains a vital lifeline for millions of Americans who rely on it for news, talk shows, sports, and, most importantly, emergency communications.

Last Congress, I co-led the effort to protect this essential part of our communications infrastructure, ensuring it continues to provide reliable information during severe weather and national emergencies.

This Congress, I am pleased to cosponsor this same effort to keep AM radio standard in all passenger vehicles.

Earlier today, I met with New Jersey members of the American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (@AAOS1) in my DC office.

We discussed the state of Medicare and the quality of care it provides, ways to improve seniors’ access to treatment, and my continued support for medical disease research that affects millions of Americans each year.

Thank you to AAOS for taking the time to meet with me.

Today, I met with Rafael Holdings, a clinical-stage biotechnology company headquartered in New Jersey. Rafael is working to develop new treatments for patients with rare and difficult-to-treat diseases. 

We discussed rare pediatric priority review vouchers, an incentive for companies developing cures for rare pediatric diseases. I have supported this important incentive in the Give Kids a Chance Act.

I appreciate the work Rafael Holdings is doing here in NJ to push the boundaries of medical innovation and to bring forward new treatments for rare pediatric diseases.

I enjoyed meeting with members of the American Car Rental Association (ACRA) today, including one of my constituents, as they visited Capitol Hill for their annual advocacy day. 

ACRA is the national trade association representing the U.S. car rental industry, with more than 300 members ranging from major brands to independent, regional, and franchise operators. 
 
We discussed the state of the rental car industry, its economic impact on communities in New Jersey & across the nation, and ACRA’s work to drive innovation & growth in mobility services for its members.

This afternoon, I welcomed members of the American Cancer Society Cancer Action Network (@ACSCAN), including several of my constituents, as part of their annual Leadership Summit & Lobby Day. 

We discussed their key priorities, including increasing funding for cancer research, expanding access to multi-cancer early detection tests for Medicare recipients, and efforts to improve the quality of life for patients across the U.S.

Our #NJ07 Law Enforcement Hometown Hero this week is Detective Brian Smith of the Bedminster Police Department.

From educating residents about credit card scams and internet fraud to visiting homes to advise them on burglary prevention, Detective Smith goes above and beyond to keep Bedminster safe.

Thank you, Detective Smith, for your incredible commitment to protecting and serving the Bedminster community!

As we reflect on the solemn anniversary of September 11th, my team participated in several memorial ceremonies across NJ-07 yesterday.

Team Kean attended more than a dozen services throughout Somerset, Union, Hunterdon, Warren, Morris, and Sussex counties. 

I am grateful to the first responders, survivors, and families of New Jerseyans who lost loved ones, whose strength and presence helps ensure their legacies live on for many years to come.

Alongside my colleagues, I urge @SecWar Hegseth to set a trial date for the terrorists responsible, to deliver justice for the families, the community, and in honor of the thousands of lives lost on that horrific day.

On September 11th, 2001, our nation endured an unspeakable tragedy, and New Jersey carried a deep share of that loss.

Thousands of our neighbors left home for work that morning and never returned.  Today, 24 years later, we honor those we lost, the first responders, the everyday citizens who became heroes, and the families who continue to carry this grief.

We remember each and every one of them, and each generation will ensure that they are never forgotten.

Yesterday, at the Problem Solvers Caucus meeting, I met with @United Airlines CEO Scott Kirby to discuss air traffic control modernization and the future of the airline industry.

Together with colleagues from both sides of the aisle, we discussed ways to improve the quality, safety, and reliability of air travel for consumers across the country.

It was great to sit down with PIM Brands and their CEO, Michael Rosenberg. Based in Park Ridge with a major facility in NJ-07, PIM is a global candy company best known for Welch’s Fruit Snacks.

We discussed trade policy, the U.S. sugar program, and ways to keep costs down for families. PIM has also been a leader in product quality, removing artificial colors long before it was common practice and helping keep families happy & healthy across the country.

Today, we remember.

On this solemn anniversary of September 11th, we honor the lives lost, the heroes who ran toward danger, and the countless families forever changed by that day. We carry in our hearts the memory of every innocent soul taken, and the pain that still lingers for those who survived, especially those still battling illnesses caused by the aftermath.

Twenty-four years have passed, but the grief is still real. And so is the strength. Out of the ashes of that unimaginable tragedy rose a more united, more resilient America. We stood together then. We stand together now.

May we always remember their names, their stories, and their sacrifice.

And may God bless America.

As we approach the 24th anniversary of the 9/11 attacks, we are reminded of how essential strong emergency communications are during a crisis.

During today's @HouseCommerce hearing, I questioned witnesses on how we can improve interoperability across our systems and keep first responders’ needs front and center. Watch the full exchange below.

If you or someone you know was affected by the 9/11 terrorist attacks, you may qualify for assistance through the September 11th Victim Compensation Fund (VCF). The VCF offers compensation to individuals, or to representatives of those who lost their lives, who were present at one of the three crash sites.

Eligibility is not limited to first responders. Those who worked or volunteered at these sites, as well as individuals who lived, worked, attended school, or visited within the VCF NYC Exposure Zone, may also qualify.

For more information, call the VCF Helpline at 1-855-885-1555 or visit https://t.co/bAe1pnCnyf.

I applaud President Trump for taking decisive action yesterday to create a designation for state sponsors of wrongful detention of Americans. In June, I joined @RepFrenchHill (AR-02), @RepMikeLawler (NY-17), @RepJoshG (NJ-05), and @RepMoskowitz (FL-23) in introducing the bipartisan Countering Wrongful Detention Act of 2025, which establishes this very designation for countries or nonstate actors that hold American citizens or permanent residents hostage. This legislation equips both the Secretary of State and Congress with new tools to hold these governments accountable by encouraging a range of penalties.
 
For my constituent, Sarah (Levinson) Moriarty, this issue hits especially close to home. Her father, Robert Levinson, was taken hostage by Iran in 2007. For years, her family lived in absolute uncertainty, wondering where he was, whether he was alive, or if they would ever see him again. Unfortunately, they never did. Far too many American families have endured that same fear, heartbreak, and loss. With this important legislation, paired with today’s executive order, we are making real strides to ensure that no family is ever forced to live through this tragedy again.
 
Hostile regimes like Iran continue to use innocent Americans as bargaining chips by dehumanizing, abusing, and in some cases killing them. This legislation would codify President Trump’s executive order and make clear that there will be consequences for using Americans as political pawns. The United States will not tolerate this behavior, and we will always stand up for our citizens, no matter where they are in the world.

My bill, the Undersea Cable Control Act, has passed the House!

Undersea cables are a vital part of global communication infrastructure, carrying 99 percent of all transoceanic digital communications, including internet data, through fiber optic networks.

I thank my colleagues in the House for supporting this crucial bill, which takes steps to prevent foreign interference, sabotage, or control of these technologies by our adversaries.

Undersea cables are vital to our economy and security, but adversaries like China are targeting them. That is why I sponsored the Undersea Cable Control Act to prevent hostile powers from accessing the key technologies used in this critical infrastructure.

Today, I spoke in support of this bill on the House floor, where it passed by voice vote and now moves to the Senate for consideration.

Our #NJ07 Law Enforcement Hometown Hero this week is Officer Giovannina Prisco of the Clark Police Department.
 
Officer Prisco’s law enforcement journey began in 2013 as a licensed EMT before she transitioned to dispatcher, special officer, and ultimately a full-time police officer. Today, she is widely recognized for her initiative, integrity, and expertise in emergency response—from earning her EMRTC certification in explosives to managing the entire department’s medical supplies.
 
Known by her colleagues for her upbeat spirit, compassion, and tireless work ethic, Officer Prisco's character is truly inspiring. Beyond the department, Officer Prisco serves as a dedicated D.A.R.E. officer, connecting with Clark’s youth and encouraging them to make positive life choices.
 
Officer Prisco, you embody the true spirit of public service. Thank you for your service to the Clark Township community!

Today is National Crypto Day of Action—a day to highlight the millions of Americans invested in crypto and the need for a clear, structured regulatory framework for both the industry and consumers.

Last month, the House passed three landmark crypto bills—the CLARITY Act, the ANTI-CBDC Surveillance State Act, and the GENIUS Act, the latter of which was ultimately signed into law by the President.

Happy Independence Day to everyone in NJ-07 and across the country!

The United States was built on the principles of freedom, liberty, and democracy—values fought for by our Founding Fathers and defended by generations of Americans since.

This afternoon, Congress passed a commonsense legislative package that was a major win for New Jerseyans and Americans across the country. We secured the full SALT deduction for every middle-class family in New Jersey. I never backed down from the fight for SALT relief, standing up to Democrats and Republicans alike to quadruple the deduction to $40,000. I also stood with American innovators, voting to renew R&D tax credits for the research and development that businesses do to fuel ingenuity and job creation.

I voted to safeguard Medicaid for every intended beneficiary in the Garden State and nationwide. By rooting out waste, fraud, and abuse, we are preserving this vital program for today’s recipients and future generations. I also voted to protect New Jersey’s expansion of certain critical supplemental payments they receive from the federal government—an important financing tool that hospitals, nursing homes, and other health care providers rely on to serve Medicaid patients. Finally, this bill allocates $50 billion over five years to hospitals and health care providers, ensuring patients continue to receive quality care in New Jersey and throughout the country.

We permanently increased the Child Tax Credit to $2,200, delivering meaningful relief to young families still struggling under the weight of four years of record inflation. We secured necessary resources for Somerset and Morris Counties, and the entire state, by investing tens of millions of dollars in local and state law enforcement to better equip them to protect President Trump and surrounding communities.

We made significant progress on key priorities like securing the border, unleashing American energy and advancement, and strengthening national security—all while cutting wasteful spending, advancing affordability, and making the federal government both more efficient and more accountable.

Once President Trump signs this bill into law, life will become more affordable for residents of New Jersey’s Seventh District. They will see immediate tax relief, greater transparency from Washington, and more support for innovation. This is a crucial step toward a stronger, more secure future for the next generation.

Current Social Security regulations include provisions that limit the ability of individuals to receive Social Security benefits, including through the government pension offset (GPO) and the windfall elimination provision (WEP).
